The paper deals with dynamic graph algorithms, which are typically studied in the computer science subfield of data structures (cs.DS). The specific problems addressed in the paper, dynamic spanner and dynamic maximal matching, are also commonly studied in the subfields of computational geometry (cs.CG) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The paper also uses randomized algorithms and probabilistic analysis, which are often studied in the subfield of numerical analysis (cs.NA). Finally, the paper presents a new black-box reduction technique, which could be relevant to the subfield of distributed computing (cs.DC).
